fn.p:
Stambaugh (1999) demonstrates that if the explanatory variable is assumed to be stationary and the disturbances of the predictive regression, equation (2), and the autoregression describing the dynamics of the explanatory variable, equation (1), are contemporaneously correlated then the presence of a predetermined explanatory variable, results in a small sample bias in the predictive regression's estimated slope coefficient. In particular,
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $E\{ \hat{\beta }-\beta \} \approx -( \sigma _{uv}/ \sigma ^{2}_{v}) T^{-1}( 1+3\rho ) $ \end{document}
                     . While this bias disappears asymptotically, we demonstrate that the effects of uncertainty surrounding the explanatory variable's order of integration do not.

Without this subsequent adjustment, the asymptotic size of the Bonferroni test,
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $S_{B}=( c,\varsigma _{1},\varsigma _{2}) $ \end{document}
                     , is conservative,
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $S_{B}=( c,\varsigma _{1},\varsigma _{2}) \leq \varsigma _{1}+\varsigma _{2}$ \end{document}
                     . We construct asymptotically valid confidence intervals having a size of 5% by setting ς2 = 5% and numerically determining that value of ς1that solves
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{\sup}_{c}S_{B}( c,\varsigma _{1,}5\% ) =5\% $ \end{document}
                     . This numerical computation is lengthy because we need to compute first‐stage confidence intervals for each realization of a Bonferroni test statistic. We thank Jim Stock for making his computer procedures for calculating these intervals available to us. Our computations are based on Monte Carlo simulations assuming time series of lengthT = 720 and 20,000 replications over an equally spaced grid ofc, − 35 ≤ c ≤ 5.

sec.p:
In this section, we investigate within the local‐to‐unity framework the asymptotic distribution of statistics based on long horizon returns. Like Richardson and Stock (1989), we also use an alternative asymptotic distribution theory for these statistics which recognizes that, even though the sample sizeTis large, the number of nonoverlapping observations may be small. As a result, conventional large‐sample approximations perform poorly in practice. Unlike Richardson and Stock, however, we do not consider the case where long horizon returns are regressed against past returns but rather are regressed against the lagged values of a stochastic explanatory variable whose order of integration, furthermore, is unknown. We follow Phillips (1987a) in deriving our asymptotic results and consider a time seriesx
