Instead of the Newey‐Westt‐statistic, which directly incorporates the return horizon and so the degree of overlap, Valkanov (2002) assesses statistical significance using the statistic
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $t/ \sqrt{T}$ \end{document}
                     wheretis the ordinary least squarest‐statistic andTis the sample size. In particular, the realized value of this statistic is compared to its asymptotic distribution under theK/T → θ limit, which depends on bothcand θ and is evaluated by Monte Carlo simulation. Of course, in any finite sample,Kis fixed and the accuracy of the test statistic's resultant asymptotic distribution depends critically on the length ofK.IfKis relatively short, the accumulated returns do not behave like anI(1) process and the asymptotic distribution will not provide a good approximation to the test statistic's finite sample distribution. As a result, Valkanov restricts his attention to relatively longer return horizons,K > 12 months, in which case this approximation is sufficiently accurate.

This requires evaluation of the distribution of
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{t}_{\hat{\beta }( K) }$ \end{document}
                     in the theorem, statement (d), using Monte Carlo simulation. We do so assuming time series of lengthT = 720 and 20,000 replications over an equally spaced grid ofc, −35 ≤ c ≤ 5, for each series estimated δ value and for each assumed value ofK(or equivalently, for each assumed value of θ for the given value ofT = 720). We subsequently adjust the asymptotic size of the Bonferroni tests to equal 5%.

sec.p:
Fromtable 4, we see that as the horizonKincreases, the corresponding confidence intervals, both traditional and Bonferroni, tend to become wider, reflecting greater uncertainty surrounding the slope coefficient β(K). However, while traditional confidence intervals are, by construction, symmetric, Bonferroni confidence intervals, which reflect uncertainty surrounding the explanatory variable's order of integration, are skewed, progressively more so as the horizonKincreases. Therefore, to the extent that
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
ewcommand\cyr{ enewcommandmdefault{wncyr} enewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} enewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} 
ormalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{	extcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}  egin{document} \landscape $\delta 
eq 0$ \end{document}
            , not knowing ρ can be seen to systematically influence inference about β(K).

However, once we explicitly acknowledge our uncertainty about ρ and rely on the Bonferroni statistics, this evidence is substantially reduced, leaving evidence only in the post‐1952 sample and then only at relatively short horizons,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $K=1$ \end{document}
            and 3 months. In this case, the cost of not knowing ρ, or equivalently not knowingc,is high because δ is estimated to be large in magnitude and close to −1; for example,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\delta }=-0.968$ \end{document}
            in the post‐1952 sample period.

Similarly, for the book‐to‐market ratio, the traditional analysis is consistent with predictability at horizons of 12 months or longer in the entire sample as well as in the pre‐1952 sample. But, once we acknowledge our uncertainty in ρ, there is no evidence of predictability at any horizon in the entire sample and only at relatively long horizons,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $K=36$ \end{document}
            and 48 months, in the pre‐1952 sample. Again, the sensitivity of inference to uncertainty surrounding the book‐to‐market ratio's order of integration is not surprising since δ is estimated to be large in magnitude and close to −1; for example,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\delta }=-0.907$ \end{document}
            for the whole sample period.

Of course, conventional tests may be appropriate, even if the explanatory variable exhibits near nonstationary behavior. While we agree with Roll (2002) that “(n)on‐stationary processes often display seemingly bizarre behavior and can easily conjure up the specter of an anomaly,” it is important to note that this behavior per se affects inference in predictive regressions only to the extent that
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
ewcommand\cyr{ enewcommandmdefault{wncyr} enewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} enewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} 
ormalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{	extcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}  egin{document} \landscape $\delta 
eq 0$ \end{document}
            and there is direct feedback from the explanatory variable to returns. For example, while the default spread clearly exhibits near nonstationary behavior, we see fromtable 4that whether or not we account for the uncertainty in the default spread's order of integration does not change our conclusion that the default spread does not forecast. This is not surprising, since in the case of the default spread, δ̂ is much smaller; for example,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
ewcommand\cyr{ enewcommandmdefault{wncyr} enewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} enewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} 
ormalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{	extcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6}  egin{document} \landscape $\hat{\delta }=-0.329$ \end{document}
            for the post‐1952 sample period.

Finally, both the term spread and the short‐term interest rate are seen to reliably forecast returns up to 3 months ahead in the post‐1952 sample period, even after explicitly acknowledging the uncertainty surrounding their order of integration. Once again, since in these cases δ is estimated to be very small,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\delta }=-0.098$ \end{document}
            in the case of the term spread and
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\hat{\delta }=-0.053$ \end{document}
            in the case of the short‐term interest rate for the post‐1952 sample, this implies that the cost of not knowing ρ is not high. Consequently, the Bonferroni intervals coincide with the corresponding traditional intervals, ensuring that our inference is robust with respect to any uncertainty surrounding these variables' order of integration.

