               . By repeating this procedure, we can construct these 97.5% confidence intervals across the grid ofcvalues and subsequently apply the Bonferroni inequality to obtain an interval with confidence of at least 95% (≡100% − (2.5% + 2.5%)), which by construction no longer depends onc.Subsequently, we follow Cavanagh et al. (1995) and adjust these confidence intervals so that the asymptotic size of the resultant Bonferroni test is 5%.

To investigate the power of our Bonferroni test in small samples, we repeat the preceding analysis, now imposing predictability by simulating one‐period returns 10,000 times over the grid β = {0,…, 0.04}. CorrespondingK‐period ahead returnsy
